      textEn: [
        "In the tenth year of Duke Zhuang’s reign, in spring, the army of Qi attacked us. The Duke was about to engage in battle when Cao Gui requested an audience. His fellow villagers said: “Those who eat meat plan such matters—why should you involve yourself?” Gui said: “Those who eat meat are shortsighted and cannot plan far ahead.” He then went in to see the Duke. He asked: “On what basis will you fight?” The Duke said: “Clothes and food that bring comfort, I dare not keep to myself but always share with others.” Gui replied: “Such small favors have not reached everyone—the people will not follow you.” The Duke said: “Sacrificial offerings of jade and silk, I dare not exaggerate but always report faithfully.” Gui replied: “Such small faithfulness has not won the trust of the gods—the gods will not bless you.” The Duke said: “In lawsuits great and small, though I cannot examine every detail, I always judge with sincerity.” Gui replied: “That is a matter of loyalty. You may fight. When you fight, please let me accompany you.”",
        "The Duke and he rode together in the same chariot and fought at Changshao. The Duke was about to sound the drum to attack. Gui said: “Not yet.” After Qi had drummed three times, Gui said: “Now!” The army of Qi was defeated and fled. The Duke was about to pursue them. Gui said: “Not yet.” He stepped down to examine their chariot tracks, then climbed the crossbar to look into the distance. He said: “Now!” And so they pursued the army of Qi.",
        "After the victory, the Duke asked the reason. Gui replied: “Battle depends on courage. The first drum raises spirits, the second weakens them, and the third exhausts them. When theirs was exhausted and ours was full, that is why we defeated them. A great state is hard to fathom—I feared an ambush. I examined their chariot tracks and found them disordered; I looked at their banners and found them toppled. That is why I pursued them.”"
      ],
